<worksheet>
  <title>Review 07-Extreme Values and sketching curves</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      <alert>Instructions:</alert> Prepare neatly written solutions to the following problems. 
      Show all relevant work and use proper notation/terminology. 
      <!--Submit these problems as a single PDF. Be sure your file is readable before submitting! -->
      Calculators should NOT be used.   
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <page>
    <exercise>
  <title>Curve Sketching Analysis: Quartic Function</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Consider the function <m>f(x) = x^4 - 2x^2 + 1</m>. Analyze its intercepts, extrema, and concavity, then sketch the graph.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      <ol marker="a.">
        <li><p><term>Intercepts:</term> <m>y</m>-int at <m>(0, 1)</m>. <m>x</m>-ints at <m>x = \pm 1</m>.</p></li>
        <li><p><term>First Derivative:</term> <m>f'(x) = 4x^3 - 4x = 4x(x^2 - 1)</m>. Critical points at <m>x = 0, \pm 1</m>.</p></li>
        <li><p><term>Extrema:</term> Minima at <m>(-1, 0)</m> and <m>(1, 0)</m>; Maximum at <m>(0, 1)</m>.</p></li>
        <li><p><term>Second Derivative:</term> <m>f''(x) = 12x^2 - 4</m>. Inflection points at <m>x = \pm \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}</m>.</p></li>
      </ol>
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="fig-quartic">
      <caption>Graph of <m>f(x) = x^4 - 2x^2 + 1</m></caption>
      <image width="60%">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            \begin{axis}[axis lines=middle, xlabel=\(x\), ylabel=\(y\), xmin=-2, xmax=2, ymin=-0.5, ymax=2]
              \addplot[blue, thick, domain=-1.8:1.8, samples=100] {x^4 - 2*x^2 + 1};
              \addplot[only marks, mark=*, blue] coordinates {(-1,0) (0,1) (1,0)};
            \end{axis}
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
  <title>Curve Sketching Analysis: Cubic Function</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Consider the function <m>g(x) = x^3 + x^2 - x - 1</m>. Analyze its intercepts, extrema, and concavity, then sketch the graph.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      <ol marker="a.">
        <li><p><term>Intercepts:</term> <m>y</m>-int at <m>(0, -1)</m>. <m>x</m>-ints at <m>x = 1, -1</m>.</p></li>
        <li><p><term>First Derivative:</term> <m>g'(x) = 3x^2 + 2x - 1 = (3x-1)(x+1)</m>. Critical points at <m>x = -1, \frac{1}{3}</m>.</p></li>
        <li><p><term>Extrema:</term> Maximum at <m>(-1, 0)</m>; Minimum at <m>(\frac{1}{3}, -\frac{32}{27})</m>.</p></li>
        <li><p><term>Second Derivative:</term> <m>g''(x) = 6x + 2</m>. Inflection point at <m>x = -\frac{1}{3}</m>.</p></li>
      </ol>
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="fig-cubic">
      <caption>Graph of <m>g(x) = x^3 + x^2 - x - 1</m></caption>
      <image width="60%">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            \begin{axis}[axis lines=middle, xlabel=\(x\), ylabel=\(y\), xmin=-2, xmax=2, ymin=-2, ymax=2]
              \addplot[red, thick, domain=-1.8:1.5, samples=100] {x^3 + x^2 - x - 1};
              \addplot[only marks, mark=*, red] coordinates {(-1,0) (0.333,-1.185)};
            \end{axis}
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>
  </solution>
</exercise>
<exercise>
  <title>Absolute Extrema on a Closed Interval</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Find the absolute maximum and absolute minimum values of <m>f(x) = x^4 - 2x^2 + 1</m> on the interval <m>[-1, 2]</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      We test the critical points within the interval (<m>x = -1, 0, 1</m>) and the endpoints (<m>x = -1, 2</m>).
      <md>
        <mrow>f(-1) \amp = (-1)^4 - 2(-1)^2 + 1 = 1 - 2 + 1 = 0</mrow>
        <mrow>f(0) \amp = (0)^4 - 2(0)^2 + 1 = 1</mrow>
        <mrow>f(1) \amp = (1)^4 - 2(1)^2 + 1 = 0</mrow>
        <mrow>f(2) \amp = (2)^4 - 2(2)^2 + 1 = 16 - 8 + 1 = 9</mrow>
      </md>
      The <term>absolute maximum</term> value is <m>9</m> (at <m>x=2</m>). The <term>absolute minimum</term> value is <m>0</m> (at <m>x=-1</m> and <m>x=1</m>).
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

</page>
</worksheet>